- Using zoom 10 tiles for detection (~152m/pixel precision) — good enough for sailing
- Water detection via RGB color matching against OSM's standard water color (#aad3df / RGB 170,211,223)
- If no water found within a single tile (~40km), show a warning and don't move the boat
- Tile images are cached in-memory so repeated nearby checks are instant
- Standard OSM tile server (tile.openstreetmap.org) supports CORS for canvas pixel reading","steps":[{"id":"step_0","description":"Step 1 — Add water detection utility functions to sailing-weather.js: Add `latLonToTilePixel(lat, lon, zoom)` to convert coordinates to tile X/Y and pixel position within the tile. Add `tilePixelToLatLon(tileX, tileY, px, py, zoom)` for reverse conversion. Add `isWaterPixel(r, g, b)` heuristic that checks if an RGB value matches OSM water color (B > 200, G > 180, R > 130, R < 200, B-R > 20). These are pure math helpers. (req 1, 2)","status":"done"},{"id":"step_1","description":"Step 2 — Add tile loading with canvas pixel sampling: Add `loadTileToCanvas(tileX, tileY, zoom)` that loads a standard OSM tile (`https://tile.openstreetmap.org/{z}/{x}/{y}.png`) into a hidden 256×256 canvas with `crossOrigin='anonymous'`. Returns a Promise resolving to the canvas 2D context. Add an in-memory tile cache (Map keyed by 'z/x/y') so repeat checks near the same location are instant. (req 1, 2, 4)","status":"done"},{"id":"step_2","description":"Step 3 — Add nearest-water scanning algorithm: Add `findNearestWater(lat, lon, callback)` that: (a) loads the tile at zoom 10 containing the position, (b) checks the exact pixel — if water, calls callback(lat, lon, false), (c) if land, scans outward in expanding square rings (up to 128px = ~19km radius), (d) on first water pixel found, converts back to lat/lon and calls callback(newLat, newLon, true), (e) if no water found in tile, calls callback(null, null, true) for graceful failure. The scan uses getImageData on the canvas context. (req 1, 2, 4)","status":"done"},{"id":"step_3","description":"Step 4 — Create validateAndSetBoatPosition wrapper: Add `validateAndSetBoatPosition(lat, lon, source)` that replaces direct position-setting. It calls `findNearestWater`, then: if on water → sets boatPosition, moves marker, calls updateInfoBar + refreshData normally; if snapped to water → shows toast ('Moved to nearest wa